        <span class='font-weight-normal'>
            This place is one of the many places the Israelites stopped on their way to the Promised Land from Egypt. After the Israelites crossed the Red Sea they began to traverse the desert of Sinai which is famous for its harsh nature where water and food are very hard to find.
            Once upon a time when the water supply was running low, the Israelites were very thirsty so they found a source of water but when they drank it the water tasted bitter and they begged Moses to give them drinkable water. Then Moses received a command from God to throw a piece of wood into the water and immediately the water turned sweet so that it was finally able to be drunk by many people (Exodus 15:23-25).
            The exact location of this place is not known with certainty but traditionally this place is known as Ain Harawah a salty water source located on the Sinai peninsula and is approximately 75 kilometers southeast of the Suez Canal.
        </span>
    </li>
    <li class='text-justify font-weight-bold mb-3'>
        <strong>ELIM
        </strong> <br>
        <span class='font-weight-normal'>
            This place is known as the resting place of the Israelites on their way to the Promised Land after passing through Mara. As it is written in Exodus 15:27 and Numbers 33:9. After they left Marah, they came to a place called Elim where there were 12 springs of water and 70 date palms.
            Based on the story in the Bible that the location of Elim was between Marah and the desert of Sinai not far from the northern coast of the Red Sea. It is possible that this place was south of where the Israelites passed and west of the desert of Sinai. So it can be concluded that Elim is in a place called Wadi Gharandel which is an oasis and is approximately 100 kilometers southeast of the Suez Canal. And after the Israelites settled for 45 days they continued their journey to Mount Sinai by crossing the Sinai desert.

        </span>
    </li>
    <li class='text-justify font-weight-bold mb-3'>
        <strong>MOUNT OF SINAI & CITY OF ST. CATHERINE
        </strong> <br>
        <span class='font-weight-normal'>
            Mount Sinai is on the Sinai peninsula. In Arabic, this mountain is called 'Jabal Musa' and has a height of 2,285 meters above sea level. In the Old Testament, this mountain is also often referred to as Mount Horeb. This mountain is one of the Sinai mountain ranges which is also the place where Moses received the 10 Commandments (Exodus 19:1-25).
            To climb to the top of Mount Sinai, you must first ride a camel for about one and a half to two hours, then proceed by walking up the stairs, which are approximately 750 steps. It might be a
            It was a tiring journey, but it was nothing compared to being at the top of Mount Sinai, enjoying the beautiful scenery, and at the same time feeling the atmosphere where God was once there and talking to Moses. The trip to the top of the mountain, best done at midnight, in order to arrive at the top at sunrise. On the top there is a chapel to commemorate the event of Moses receiving the 10 Commandments.
            At the foot of Mount Sinai is a monastery building, which according to tradition was built on a burning bush, when God appeared to Moses (Exodus 3:2). This monastery is called the Monastery of St. Catherine, named after Saint Catherine who was martyred in the 4th century, and her bones are stored on the top of Mount Catherine. The monastery was built in the 5th century and is currently run by the Greek Orthodox Church.

            Not far from this monastery there is a rock mountain which in one part is shaped like an ox. This is reminiscent of the event when the nation
            Israel made an image of an ox for them to worship, because Moses never came and this angered Moses against the Israelites (Exodus 32:1-35).

        </span>
    </li>
    <li class='text-justify font-weight-bold mb-3'>
        <strong>THE SHEPHERD FIELD (BETHLEHEM)</strong> <br>
        <span class='font-weight-normal'>
            Not far from the Church of the Nativity there is a small town or village called Beit Sahour. This is where lies the Shepherd Field or The Shepherd Field which used to be a place where shepherds grazed their cattle.
            On the night of the birth of Jesus, the shepherds were surprised by the arrival of the Angel of the Lord in His glory who announced to them the news of the birth of Jesus Christ.
            At the top of the gate to the Shepherd's Field, there is the inscription Gloria In Excelsis Deo as a memorial to the song of glory sung by the angels in front of the shepherds.
            The cool and calm impression was felt when you first entered the Padang Shepherd complex. This is due to the large number of trees growing on the left and right sides of the road entering the location. In the center of the Padang Shepherd complex stands a statue of a shepherd holding a stick and below it there are statues of sheep that form a water fountain.
            Inside the Shepherd's Field complex there is a chapel belonging to the Roman Catholic Church called the Chapel of the Shepherd Field. This chapel was built to commemorate the appearance of the angels before the shepherds. In addition, there are several caves that used to be shelters for shepherds and their livestock, which have now been converted into places of prayer or worship for pilgrims who come to this place.
        </span>
    </li>
    <li class='text-justify font-weight-bold mb-3'>
        <strong>CHURCH OF NATIVITY (BETHLEHEM)</strong> <br>
        <span class='font-weight-normal'>
            This church began construction in 325 on the orders of Emperor Constantine and was completed in 565 and is the oldest church in the Holy Land. Since 2012, the church has been registered as a World Heritage Site by UNESCO.
            There are three denominations in this church complex, namely the Greek Orthodox Church in the center of the church and visible directly from the church entrance. Then the Armenian Church which is in the same location as the Greek Orthodox Church is just a bit back and its position is near the Nativity Cave and the Roman Catholic Church which is on the outside of the Greek Orthodox Church.
            This church is always crowded with pilgrims. If it is in a busy season, pilgrims even need approximately 1-2 hours in line to enter and see the Nativity Cave, and in the cave also should not linger because it will hinder the queue that will enter the next.
            To enter into this church one had to pass through a door so low that people had to bow their heads. At the bottom of this building is the Nativity Cave which is believed to be the place where Jesus was born. His birth was marked by the light of a star which later became a guide for the Wise Men to come to Jesus. There is a ladder to the right of the altar as a way to enter the Cave of the Nativity.
            Beside the Church of the Nativity there is a Roman Catholic Church called the Church of St. Catherine, which was founded in memory of St. Catherine of Alexandria. This church was completed in 1882. In front of this church stands a statue in honor of St. Jerome or Jerome, who was a translator of the Bible into Latin known as the Vulgate. Jerome died in Bethlehem in 420 AD.
            Every December at the Church of the Nativity there is always a Christmas Mass which is broadcast throughout the world. In addition, a Bethlehem Christmas festival was also held and a large Christmas tree was installed in Manger Square, which is the field in front of the church.

        </span>
    </li>
    <li class='text-justify font-weight-bold mb-3'>
        <strong>THE ASCENCION CHAPEL (JERUSALEM)</strong> <br>
        <span class='font-weight-normal'>
            At the location of Jesus' ascension to Heaven, on the top of the Mount of Olives, East Jerusalem now stands a chapel called the Chapel of the Ascension. Previously this chapel was a church called the Church of The Holy Ascencion, but in 1187 it was seized by Sultan Salahudin and later converted into a mosque until now.
            Although it has been converted into a mosque, this chapel is still maintained and now this chapel is in the At-Tur Mosque complex and has been guarded by Muslim families for a long time and pilgrims can still enter this chapel to pray.
            Inside this chapel there is a stone that is believed to be the place where Jesus stood before ascending to Heaven.

        </span>
    </li>
    <li class='text-justify font-weight-bold mb-3'>
        <strong>CHURCH OF PATER NOSTER (JERUSALEM)</strong> <br>
        <span class='font-weight-normal'>
            One of the teachings of Jesus is about Prayer, and the famous prayer that Jesus taught directly is the Lord's Prayer, which is still said by all Christians in the world.
            As a reminder of this, somewhere on the top of the Mount of Olives, Jerusalem was built a church called the Church of the Lord's Prayer or Father Noster Church.
            This church is a Roman Catholic church, originally built by Emperor Constantine in the 4th century and given the name Eleona Church, after the Emperor's mother, Queen Eleona or Helena. But in 614 this church was destroyed by the Persians. After undergoing several renovations, the current church is a new church built in 1875. Until now this church is part of and managed by the Carmelite Order, which is based in France.
            it is filled with plants that make the atmosphere cool. Around this church yard there is a plant called Ziziphus Spina Christi, which is a kind of small tree with sharp branches and was used as a crown of thorns that was placed on the head of Jesus Christ when He was crucified.
            Inside the church, there are writings of the Lord's Prayer in various languages ​​which are posted throughout the church, including Indonesian and several regional languages ​​in Indonesia.

        </span>
    </li>
    <li class='text-justify font-weight-bold mb-3'>
        <strong>PALM SUNDAY ROAD (JERUSALEM)</strong> <br>
        <span class='font-weight-normal'>
            When he was about to enter Jerusalem, Jesus was greeted with great joy by many people, praising God for all His miraculous deeds and spreading their clothes on the path that Jesus walked. At that time Jesus rode on a donkey and passed a road that descended from the Mount of Olives.
            Today the event is still commemorated by Christians. This observance is called Palm Sunday where people walk down a path that is thought to be the same as the one Jesus walked, carrying palm fronds. The road is now called Palm Sunday Road or Palm Sunday Road.

        </span>
    </li>
    <li class='text-justify font-weight-bold mb-3'>
        <strong>DOMINUS FLEVIT CHURCH (JERUSALEM)</strong> <br>
        <span class='font-weight-normal'>
            To commemorate the incident of Jesus weeping over Jerusalem (Luke 13:33-35), then on the slopes of the Mount of Olives a church was built named Dominus Flevit which means God Weeping and indeed the shape of this church resembles tears. This Roman Catholic church was built on the ruins of an earlier church that dates back to Byzantine times and was completed in 1955.
            In this church there is a window in this church that faces the city of Jerusalem, precisely towards the old city, which indicates that Jesus had seen the City of Jerusalem from this place.

        </span>
    </li>
    <li class='text-justify font-weight-bold mb-3'>
        <strong>GARDEN OF GETHSEMANE & CHURCH OF ALL NATIONS (JERUSALEM)</strong> <br>
        <span class='font-weight-normal'>
            This garden is the scene where Jesus was captured by Roman soldiers while He was praying (Matthew 26:36-56). Gethsemane is taken from the Aramaic Gad Smane which means oil squeeze. Previously Jesus and His disciples often visited this place, that's why Judas knew where he had to find Jesus and together with the Roman soldiers came to arrest Him.
            This garden is filled with Olive Trees and is located at the foot of the Mount of Olives and still exists today.
            Among the many olive trees, there is one olive tree which is estimated to be more than 2000 years old. This means that this tree has existed since the time of Jesus Christ and was a silent witness to the arrest of Jesus. Now the tree is still standing but supported by a wire fence around it.
            In the Garden of Gethsemane there is a church called The Church of All Nations. The church began construction in 1919 and was completed in 1924, with architect Antonio Barluzzi.
            It was named the Church of All Nations because the construction of this church was funded by twelve countries. It is marked by the twelve domes on the roof of the church. This church is also known as the Church of Agony, which means suffering.
            At the altar of this church there is a stone that is believed to be the place where Jesus prayed the night before He was arrested for trial.

        </span>
    </li>
    <li class='text-justify font-weight-bold mb-3'>
        <strong>UPPER ROOM (JERUSALEM)</strong> <br>
        <span class='font-weight-normal'>
            On the eve of His death Jesus had the opportunity to have the last supper with His disciples. This event became known as the Last Supper. At this supper Jesus said several important things to His disciples including that He would be betrayed by Judas and denied three times by Peter.
            Place of the Last Supper in Latin this place is called the Cenacle, which means dinning room or dining room. Also known as the Upper Room, because it is located on the 2nd floor of a building on Mount Zion, Jerusalem. Due to the turmoil of wars in the past, this place has undergone several changes in its function, from a church to a mosque, and now it is a public place.

        </span>
    </li>
    <li class='text-justify font-weight-bold mb-3'>
        <strong>CHURCH OF ST. PETER IN GALICATU (JERUSALEM)</strong> <br>
        <span class='font-weight-normal'>
            After being arrested in the Garden of Gethsemane, Jesus was brought by his captors to the Religious Court for trial. Peter and the other disciples followed him quietly. Jesus had previously warned Peter that he would deny Jesus three times before the rooster crowed and it was when Jesus was tried that Jesus' warning came true, where Peter openly denied Jesus in front of people—people who asked him who he was.
            The place where Jesus was tried and Peter denied Jesus today stands a church called The Church of St. Peter In Gallicantu or Church of the Rooster Crows. The church was built on a site believed to have been the home of the High Priest Caiaphas.
            Before there was this church, there was a Byzantine Chapel which was built in 457 BC, but was destroyed in 1010 by the Fatimid Caliph Al-Hakim bin Amr Allah.
            Then the Chapel was rebuilt by the Crusaders in 1102 and given its present name. After the fall of Jerusalem, the church collapsed again and was not rebuilt until 1931 before the church that exists today is established.
            The church is located outside the walls of the old city of Jerusalem, to the east of Mount Zion, in it there is a place where Jesus was lodged or detained before He was crucified and there is also a memorial statue of Peter denying Jesus three times.

        </span>
    </li>
    <li class='text-justify font-weight-bold mb-3'>
        <strong>BETHESDA POOL/POOL OF BETHESDA (JERUSALEM)</strong> <br>
        <span class='font-weight-normal'>
            In Jerusalem there is a pool that is always visited by many sick people. They believe that at any time the Angel of the Lord descends into the pool and shakes the water and after that whoever enters the pool, whatever his illness will be cured. One time Jesus came to the pool and met a man who had been sick for 38 years and had never had the chance to enter the pool. And at that time Jesus performed a miracle on the man and he was healed happen without the person entering the pool.
            The pool in question is Bethesda or Bethesda. This pool is still there today, but there is no water anymore. Located within the Old City of Jerusalem today not far from the Lion's Gate. This pool is rectangular in size with a size of 106 X 60 square meters with a depth of about 7 meters and is surrounded by 4 porches and 1 separate portico, just as it is written in the Gospel of John 5:2-3.

        </span>
    </li>
    <li class='text-justify font-weight-bold mb-3'>
        <strong>CHURCH OF ST. ANNA/CHURCH OF ST. ANNA (JERUSALEM)</strong> <br>
        <span class='font-weight-normal'>
            Adjacent to the Bethesda pool is a church, the Church of Santa Anna, which was built in the 12th century by Crusaders just above the ruins of an old church built in the 5th century. This church has very good acoustics, so if someone sings in this church there will be a beautiful echo of voice. According to tradition, the location of this church is the residence of Anna and Joachim, who were the parents of Our Lady, as well as the place of her birth.
        </span>
    </li>
    <li class='text-justify font-weight-bold mb-3'>
        <strong>VIA DOLOROSA (JERUSALEM)</strong> <br>
        <span class='font-weight-normal'>
            Before serving his sentence, Jesus first had to pass a road that became known as the Via Dolorosa or the path of suffering, which started from the place where He was executed to the hill of Golgotha ​​or Calvary. Catholic tradition records that there were fourteen stations or fourteen places where Jesus rested when He took up the cross. Today's Via Dolorosa is located in
            Jerusalem's Old City, and almost all of its streets are in Muslim quarters. The Old City of Jerusalem is divided into four parts, known as the Quarter.
            Along Via Dolorosa is now full of shops selling various items ranging from clothes, food to souvenirs. But at every point of the fourteen stops a sign is marked so that pilgrims can know it.
            Here is an explanation of the fourteen stops along Via Dolorosa:
            1st Station: The place where Jesus was sentenced to death by Pontius Pilate.
            2nd Station: This is where Jesus was given a cross and then carried it himself by carrying it up to the place of punishment, namely a hill called Golgotha.
            3rd Station: The place where Jesus fell for the first time on His way to the place of the crucifixion.
            4th Station: The place where when Jesus was carrying the cross, He met Mary, His Mother who was also there and witnessed the suffering of His Son.
            5th Station: Here Jesus gets help from a man from a region in Libya, named Simon of Cyrene, who replaces Jesus to carry His cross.
            6th Station: Tradition records that in this place Jesus met a woman who wiped His face with a cloth, on which the image of Jesus' face was imprinted. The woman was later known as Veronika, a name taken from a combination of Greek and Latin which means True Image (Vera = True; Icon = Image).
            7th Station: Because of extreme exhaustion, Jesus fell a second time.
            8th Station: Among the many people who witnessed Jesus' journey to Golgotha ​​there were several women who had experienced the miracles of Jesus and they witnessed the suffering and wept. In a state of suffering, Jesus was still able to comfort the women.
            9th Station: At a place that is almost close to the place of his crucifixion, namely Golgotha, Jesus falls again for the third time.
            From the Tenth Station to the Fourteenth Station they are all in the same location, which is called the Church of The Holy Sepulchre or Church of the Holy Sepulchre.
            10th Station: This is where Jesus began to be undressed, before being raised to the cross.
            11th Station: This is where Jesus begins to be crucified. His body was laid on the cross, then His hands and feet were nailed. After that the cross was lifted so that it stood upright on the ground.
            12th Station: This stop is a memorial of Jesus' death on the cross, at three o'clock in the evening before the Sabbath. Marked by the cry Eli, Eli, Lama Sabakhtani which means my God, my God, why have you forsaken me.
            13th Station: This is where Jesus is taken down from the cross, then cleansed before being buried.
            14th Station: This is the place where Jesus was buried before finally rising on the third day.
        </span>
    </li>
    <li class='text-justify font-weight-bold mb-3'>
        <strong>CHURCH OF THE HOLY SEPULCHRE (JERUSALEM)</strong> <br>
        <span class='font-weight-normal'>
            The Church of the Holy Sepulchre or the Church of the Holy Sepulcher is believed by many Christians as the place where the crucifixion took place and since the 4th century has been visited by pilgrims to commemorate the sacrifice of Jesus Christ. As stated in the previous section, in this church there are five a station or stop on the Via Dolorosa which signifies the suffering of Jesus.
            The church, which was built in 325, is now jointly managed by four church denominations, namely the Roman Catholic Church, the Greek Orthodox Church, the Syrian Orthodox Church and the Ethiopian Orthodox Church. The roof of this church dome-shaped, as is usually the case for houses of worship in the Middle East. One thing that is unique about this church is that the caretaker comes from a Muslim family and this has happened for dozens of generations.

        </span>
    </li>
    <li class='text-justify font-weight-bold mb-3'>
        <strong>THE WAITERING WALL/WESTERN WALL (JERUSALEM)</strong> <br>
        <span class='font-weight-normal'>
            One of the pilgrimage destinations in Jerusalem's Old City is the Western Wall, which is a holy place for Judaism. People also often refer to it as the Wailing Wall.
            This wall is part of the remaining part of the wall surrounding the last temple building, which was built by Herod in 20 BC. In the year 70, General Titus invaded the city of Jerusalem and destroyed the existing buildings including the Temple, but he left this part of the wall along with its large stones to show the world how great the Roman army was.
            Today, the Western Wall has become like a place of worship for the Jews. On Saturdays or Sabbaths, this wall is crowded with Jews to pray there. In front of the Wailing Wall there is a large field that is provided for thousands of people who want to worship.
        </span>
    </li>
    <li class='text-justify font-weight-bold mb-3'>
        <strong>THE GARDEN TOMB (JERUSALEM)</strong> <br>
        <span class='font-weight-normal'>
            In 1883, a British general named Charles Gordon found a rock hill that looks like a skull. After seeing the hill, he thought and concluded that this place was the hill of the skull which was the place where Jesus was crucified. Not far from the location was also found a stone tomb that is thought to be from the first century.
            The shape that resembles a skull is now not clearly visible, because it has been filled with asphalt roads. This is due to the presence of a bus terminal in front of this hill.
            Some scholars suggest that this was the actual site of Jesus' crucifixion, as it was outside the city walls of Jerusalem and on the side of the road. This opinion is inferred from what is narrated in the four Gospels that the soldiers took Jesus out of the city and the Roman tradition of crucifixion was carried out in a place where the crowd could see, because it was for a memorial. And the streets where the skull hill was found was once the main street where people passed by.
            To commemorate the event of the Resurrection of Jesus, a site was built next to the skull hill found by General Charles Gordon, because there is also a tomb that is thought to date from the first century.
            The place which was later named The Garden Tomb or the Garden Tomb was purchased by a non-profit organization in 1982 to later be treated and turned into a historic site. The location is north of the Damascus Gate, the Old City of Jerusalem.
            In this garden there is an empty tomb that is thought to be the tomb of Jesus, then a garden and a former winepress which is thought to also date to the first century and a giant water reservoir. It is thought that this once belonged to Joseph of Arimathea, who gave his tomb to Jesus.
            Then what about the views of other Christians who say that the Tomb of Jesus is in the Old City of Jerusalem or the Church of The Holy Sepulcher? There is no need to be confused by the existence of these two views, because indeed all these places are determined based on estimates and past Christian traditions, there is no detailed record from the Bible regarding the exact location of Jesus being crucified and buried. But one thing is certain for all who believe that Jesus Christ really died, was buried and resurrected and that is clearly written by the four Gospels.

        </span>
    </li>
    <li class='text-justify font-weight-bold mb-3'>
        <strong>DEAD SEA (DEAD SEA)</strong> <br>
        <span class='font-weight-normal'>
            The Dead Sea or Dead Sea is the most unique sea in the world. Because there is no material that can sink in this sea. Even people who can't swim will be able to float in this sea. This sea stretches over the territories of Israel, Palestine and Jordan and is located at 417 meters below sea level, which makes it the lowest sea or lake in the world. In the Bible the name for this sea is the Salt Sea (Deuteronomy 3:17).
            Named the Dead Sea because no life forms can survive in the sea which has the highest salt content in the world, which is about 32% (compared to ordinary sea water which has an average salt content of only 3%). This sea has a length of 67 kilometers, a width of 18 kilometers and a surface area of ​​810 square kilometers, with a depth of 378 meters.
            The Dead Sea is rich in various minerals, therefore factories are built around it to process these minerals. Mineral substances contained include magnesium, zinc, calcium, potassium, sulfur, chlorine, sodium, and many more. In addition, this mud from the sea has properties that are good for health, especially for the skin, namely to smooth the skin and face, it can also accelerate blood circulation.
            In the southern part of the Dead Sea, there is a location that is thought to be the ruins of the cities of Sodom and Gomorrah which were destroyed by God in Old Testament times. Even on one side of the rocky hills, there is a protruding rock that is thought by people to be Lot's wife who had turned into a Pillar of Salt, because she looked back when the city of Sodom was destroyed (Genesis 19:26).

        </span>
    </li>
    <li class='text-justify font-weight-bold mb-3'>
        <strong>QUMRAN</strong> <br>
        <span class='font-weight-normal'>
            Qumran is the location of the discovery of scrolls of scripture by the Bedouin Tribe, which is a herding tribe scattered in the Middle East region.
            They took the discovery to a Syrian Christian and sold it. By the Syrians this discovery was taken to Jerusalem, until it was finally recognized as ancient Hebrew writing.
            After the end of the 1967 war, Israel took control of this area and immediately came under the supervision of the Israel National Parks Authority. The Israeli government invested heavily in conducting research and archeological excavations at this site.
            And in 1949 an excavation expedition began to search for and find other scrolls. One by one the scrolls began to gather. Scholars believe that the scrolls came from a community that existed in 125-68 BC.
            Eventually all the scrolls were found, and they are currently kept in a special museum at the Hebrew University, Jerusalem.

        </span>
    </li>
    <li class='text-justify font-weight-bold mb-3'>
        <strong>HILL OF TEMPTAION/MOUNT OF TEMPTAION (YERICHO)</strong> <br>
        <span class='font-weight-normal'>
            Mount of Temptation, a barren rocky hill. This hill, which is located in the Judean Desert, is in Arabic called Jabal al-Quruntul or Deir Al Qarantal which means Mountain of Forty Days, to remember that Jesus fasted for 40 days. This hill has a height of 360 meters and stretches from the northwest of the city of Jericho to the West Bank.
            In the middle of this hill there is a Greek Orthodox monastery called the Monastery of Temptation which means the Monastery of Temptation. This monastery was built for
            commemorates the time when Jesus was tempted by the devil. The pilgrims can reach this monastery by using the Cable Car that has been provided. The city of Jericho is the closest city to this Mount of Temptation. From the top of the Monastery of Temptation, you can clearly see a panoramic view of the city of Jericho.

        </span>
    </li>
    <li class='text-justify font-weight-bold mb-3'>
        <strong>ZACHEUS' SYCAMOR TREE (JERICHHO)</strong> <br>
        <span class='font-weight-normal'>
            While Jesus was in Jericho, He met Zacchaeus, a tax collector who intended to entertain Jesus at his house. The encounter between Jesus and Zacchaeus is quite unique, because Zacchaeus is a short person, so he has to climb a tree to see Jesus. The tree that Zacchaeus climbed when he met Jesus was a Sycamore fig tree. A similar tree can now be seen on a street in the city of Jericho, the tree is in a garden and surrounded by a fence, and is used as a memorial to the event of the meeting between Jesus and Zacchaeus.
        </span>
    </li>
    <li class='text-justify font-weight-bold mb-3'>
        <strong>CAESAREA MARITIMA</strong> <br>
        <span class='font-weight-normal'>
            Caesarea Maritima is an ancient city located on the shores of the Mediterranean Sea or the Mediterranean Sea between Tel Aviv City and Haifa City. A Harbor was built by King Herod the Great in 9 BC. The city that was once the capital of the Roman province of Judea is now in ruins and about 2 kilometers to the south stands the modern city of Caesarea which has a population of about 5000 inhabitants. The city is the only Israeli territory managed by a private organization, the Caesarea Development Corporation.
            In the former ruins of the ancient city can still be seen an aqueduct or aquaduct on the coast of the Mediterranean Sea which is thought to have existed since Roman times and the former Roman Theatre. These sites were included in Caesarea National Park in 2011.

        </span>
    </li>
    <li class='text-justify font-weight-bold mb-3'>
        <strong>HAIFA</strong> <br>
        <span class='font-weight-normal'>
            Haifa is the largest port city and also the third largest city in Israel with a population of approximately 265,000 people and an area of ​​63,666 square kilometers. It was originally a small town with 10,000 inhabitants at the beginning of the 20th century. The name Haifa first appears in the 3rd century before, in a Talmudic literature. The city is located on the coast of the Mediterranean Sea and is at the foot of the Carmel Mountains.
            The city of Haifa is also the world center of the Baha'i faith, which has a following of approximately 6 million people. Baha'i is a belief originating from Iran that teaches the principles of the oneness of God, the unity of religion and the unity of the human race). This is marked by the establishment of a garden which is the center of pilgrimage for the Baha'i people, namely the Baha'i Garden or the Baha'i Garden in the valley of Mount Carmel.
        </span>
    </li>
    <li class='text-justify font-weight-bold mb-3'>
        <strong>CHURCH OF ANNUNCIATION (NAZARETH)</strong> <br>
        <span class='font-weight-normal'>
            This church is the largest church in the entire Middle East region and consists of two floors, which are also called the Upper Church which is the main part and the Lower Church where there is Mary's house when she received news from the Angel Gabriel. .
            The current church is a new building from the old church which was demolished in 1954. The architect of this new church is an Italian named Giovanni Muzio. In 1969 the construction of this church was completed and is now managed by the Roman Catholic Church.
            On the front wall of this church there is a painting that symbolizes the four Gospel writers namely Matthew, Mark, Luke and John, each of which is depicted holding a symbol, namely the symbol of the Divine Man which Matthew holds because his Gospel emphasizes the coming of Jesus as a human, then the symbol of the Divine Man. The Winged Lion held by Mark because the writer of this Gospel saw Jesus as the Lion of the Tribe of Judah, then Luke held the Winged Ox because he described Jesus as the Atonement for the sins of mankind, and finally John who held the Eagle because John's Gospel is a gospel that has a higher thought compared to other Bibles, therefore likened to an eagle that is able to fly higher than other birds.
            In addition, right under the painting of the four Gospel writers, there is an inscription in Latin, namely Verbum Caro F actum Et Habitavit In Nobis, which means that the Word became Man and dwelt among us (John 1:14).
            The exterior of the front door of the church depicts the life journey of Jesus Christ from His birth to His death, resurrection and ascension to Heaven. While in the church yard there are various paintings of the Virgin Mary from various versions according to countries in the world, including from Indonesia, where the painting depicts Mother Mary wearing a kebaya which is Indonesia's national dress.

        </span>
    </li>
    <li class='text-justify font-weight-bold mb-3'>
        <strong>KANA</strong> <br>
        <span class='font-weight-normal'>
            Cana was the first place that Jesus and His disciples visited when they were about to begin ministry. Cana is a city in the Galilee region, which is where Jesus performed his first miracle, when He was invited to a wedding. While the party was going on, they ran out of wine. And that's when Jesus performed a miracle by changing the water into wine, which then turned the wine into wine that was better in quality than the wine that was served first.
            At the venue of this party, there is currently a church, namely the Wedding Church at Cana or the Wedding Church in Cana. The church, which is managed by the Franciscan Order, began construction in 1881 and was completed in 1905. Archaeological excavations found that before this church building was built, this place used to be a synagogue or place of worship for the Jews that existed around the 4th century AD.
            In this church, husband and wife pilgrims usually carry out a kind of procession of confirming their marriage vows that have been previously done to their respective partners.
            And not a few brides and grooms are married in this place. Because remembering at the time of Jesus this place used to be a wedding and there
            also miracles happen, so the couples hope and believe that a miracle will happen in their marriage.
            This church has several rooms that can be used for pilgrims to worship or perform marriage confirmation rituals and in the lower room of the main building can be seen an original jar of wine storage from the time of Jesus.
            The city of Cana is also famous for its wine. Along the highway near the church and the road leading to the church there are many shops selling bottled wines in both large and small sizes and can be brought as souvenirs from the Holy Land.
        </span>
    </li>
    <li class='text-justify font-weight-bold mb-3'>
        <strong>YARDENIT (GALILEA)</strong> <br>
        <span class='font-weight-normal'>
            Yardenit The Baptismal is a site on the headwaters of the Jordan River, where water from the Sea of ​​Galilee enters the Jordan and then flows to the Dead Sea. This place is an alternative place of baptism for pilgrims who come from all over the world.
        </span>
    </li>
    <li class='text-justify font-weight-bold mb-3'>
        <strong>Mount Tabor (GALILEA)</strong> <br>
        <span class='font-weight-normal'>
            Mount Tabor is located in the southern part of the Lower Galilee region or Lower Galilee, about 18 kilometers west of the Sea of ​​Galilee. As a commemoration of the Exalted Jesus incident that had occurred on this mountain (Matthew 17:1-13), on the top of the mountain a church was built by the Franciscan Order which was named the Church of the Transfiguration which was designed by Italian Architect Antonio Barluzzi and was completed in 1924.
            In this church there are 3 chapels, namely the Elijah Chapel and the Moses Chapel on the right and left of the building, as well as the chapel to honor Jesus in the center, which is the largest part.
            From the top of this church you can see the beautiful view of the Jezrel Valley. And because the road to the church is steep and winding and not wide, this route cannot be traversed by buses, but by small cars that can accommodate up to 15 people at the foot of the mountain.
            On the slopes of Mount Tabor there is an Arab village named Daburieh. This name was given to honor Nabiah Deborah who was a judge during the war between Barak and Panglima Sisera, where Deborah was also the leader of the war along with Barak at that time (Judges 4:1-24).

        </span>
    </li>
    <li class='text-justify font-weight-bold mb-3'>
        <strong>CHURCH OF MOUNT OF BEATITUDES (GALILEA)</strong> <br>
        <span class='font-weight-normal'>
            One of the famous ministries of Jesus was when He spoke to many people from the top of a hill. This event is known as the Sermon on the Mount. The Gospel of Matthew records Jesus' sermon on the Mount in two chapters that contain teachings—teachings on: Beatitudes, Salt of the Earth and Light of the World, Jesus and the Law, Giving Alms, Prayer, Fasting, Accumulating Treasures, Anxiety, Judgment , The Holy and Precious Things, The Answering of Prayers, The Right Way, The False Teachings and The Two Kinds Of Basics. Everyone who was in the place at that time was amazed after hearing Jesus' powerful teaching.
            One part of Jesus' famous sermon which was later commemorated by the founding of a church called the Church of The Mount Beatitudes or the Church of the Mount of Beatitudes is the sermon on the beatitudes (Matthew 5:3-12).
            This church is built on a hill which is believed to be the place where Jesus used to preach. Designed by Italian architect Antonio Barluzzi this church was built in 1937 and has a beautiful shape and looks beautiful coupled with a view of the Sea of ​​Galilee in the background.
            Before entering the church building, pilgrims can enjoy the beautiful view of the green garden filled with colorful flowers and along the entrance there are stones - stones carved with happy words preached by Jesus.

        </span>
    </li>
    <li class='text-justify font-weight-bold mb-3'>
        <strong>TABGHA (GALILEA)</strong> <br>
        <span class='font-weight-normal'>
            This is the location where Jesus fed 5000 people and now a church called The Church of Multiplication of The Loaves and Fish is being built, which is located in an area whose name is Tabgha. Tabgha is taken from the Greek 'Heptaegon' which means Seven Springs.
            At the altar of this church there is a boulder that is believed to be the place where Jesus broke bread and fish to be distributed to the people who were there at that time. On the altar floor there is a mosaic depicting a basket containing four loaves of bread and two fish. His basket only contained four loaves of bread because the fifth loaf was Jesus who was described as the Bread of Life (John 6:35).
            In the outer courtyard of this church there is a replica of a millstone, a stone that was used to grind grain and can also be used to press olives into oil.
            This church was originally a small chapel, built in the early 4th century AD, but then was destroyed by the Persians and rebuilt in 1934 into a church which was then refined again in 1982 so that it becomes what it is today and the church is now under the care and supervision of the Benedictine Order. of the Roman Catholic Church.
            Finally, in June 2015, this church was again burned by unknown people but did not burn the entire building, only a few parts of the outside were affected. After being repaired, the church can now be visited again.

        </span>
    </li>
    <li class='text-justify font-weight-bold mb-3'>
        <strong>CHURCH OF ST. PETER THE MAIN/CHURCH OF ST. PETER PRIMACY (GALILEA)</strong> <br>
        <span class='font-weight-normal'>
            The Church of The Primacy of Saint Peter was built to commemorate the conversation between Jesus and Simon Peter after His resurrection (John 12:1-19). The church, which is located right on the east coast of the Sea of ​​Galilee, is adjacent to the Church of the Multiplication, Tabgha. This church was opened in 1933 and is currently managed by the Franciscan Order.
            Inside the church building there is a rock called Mensa Kristi or Christ's Table which is believed to be the place where Jesus gave food to His disciples.

        </span>
    </li>
    <li class='text-justify font-weight-bold mb-3'>
        <strong>CAPERNAUM</strong> <br>
        <span class='font-weight-normal'>
            Capernaum was an important city at the time of Jesus' ministry, because this is where Jesus lived for a while and from this city Jesus traveled around Galilee with His disciples (Mark 6:6b). In this city also Jesus taught and performed miracles, among others, healed the captain's servant Capernaum who was sick (Matthew 8:5-13) and also healed Peter's mother-in-law who was sick with a fever (Matthew 8:14-17).
            Because this city became a kind of center or base camp for Jesus' ministry, then this city was referred to as 'His Own City' or the City of Jesus (Matthew 9:1). Capernaum itself comes from the Hebrew 'Kfar Nahum' which means the village of Nahum. In the end Jesus condemned Capernaum for the unbelief of its inhabitants and He foretold the fall of this city (Matthew 11:23-24).
            Now Capernaum is only the ruins of buildings from the past and is no longer inhabited by residents. Capernaum is now one of the most important spiritual sites visited by many pilgrims from all over the world.
            Inside this site complex, there are several buildings, including the ruins of a synagogue or a Jewish religious house of worship, a new Catholic Church built right above the ruins of Peter's mother-in-law's house, then a statue of Peter holding the keys to the kingdom of heaven and a statue of a sleeping person near the entrance. , by a Canadian sculptor and named Homeless Jesus which depicts the Son of Man having no place to lay His head (Matthew 8:20).

        </span>
    </li>
    <li class='text-justify font-weight-bold mb-3'>
        <strong>LAKE OF GALILEA</strong> <br>
        <span class='font-weight-normal'>
            In the region of Galilee there is a famous freshwater lake which is a silent witness to the ministry of Jesus with His disciples. On the shores of this lake Jesus began to call His disciples who were fishing, then Jesus preached on Peter's boat, Jesus also calmed the storm and even walked on this lake during a storm, and finally after His resurrection, He appeared to the people. disciples are also on the shores of this lake. Memories of the story of Jesus' ministry are stored in this lake.
            The lake in question is called the Sea of ​​Galilee, after the name of the region. In addition, there are several names for this lake, including Kinnereth Lake which means harp or harp, because when viewed from above this lake is shaped like a harp, then it is also called Lake Genesareth, which is another word for kinnereth and the Tiberian Sea because on the west bank of this lake there is a city called Tiberias.
            The Sea of ​​Galilee has an area of ​​166 square kilometers with a length of 21 kilometers, a width of 13 kilometers, while its depth is about 43 meters and is the lowest freshwater lake on earth and the second lowest lake on earth after the Dead Sea. This lake is a source of water for Israel and as a source of food because of the many fish that live in it.
            The main water source of this lake is the Jordan River which flows from the north of the lake and then exits to the south of the lake through a dam called Degania.
            The city on the shores of the lake is named Tiberias which is located on the west coast of the lake. The city was founded in the year 20 and currently has a population of approximately 45,000 inhabitants.
            The name Tiberias was given in honor of the Roman Emperor, Tiberius. Tiberias is also one of the four holy cities for the Jewish people.
            The pilgrims can enjoy the atmosphere of this lake by sailing on a wooden boat engine that is widely available on the shores of the lake. It usually takes about 45 minutes to 1 hour to go around this lake. And from mid-spring until the end of winter, which is around mid-November to March, around this lake there are lots of seagulls or seagulls.

        </span>
    </li>
    <li class='text-justify font-weight-bold mb-3'>
        <strong>MOUNT OF NEBO/MOUNT OF NEBO</strong> <br>
        <span class='font-weight-normal'>
            According to the Old Testament, Mount Nebo was the place where Moses looked to the Promised Land. Moses stopped at this mountain because God was not allowed to enter the Promised Land (Deuteronomy 32:49-52).
            Mount Nebo is located in the western part of Jordan, has an altitude of 817 meters above sea level. If the weather is good and it is not foggy, then from the top of the mountain you can see the expanse of the Promised Land, namely the Jordan River valley and the city of Jericho. There is a map indicating the promised land made of wood on the top of this mountain. This is the final resting place of the Prophet Moses. Although the exact location is not known, it is believed that Moses was buried on this mountain.
            There is a church on the Peak of Mount Nebo, which is a remnant of a church that was built in the 4th century, and was discovered in 1933. Inside this church were found 6 tombs covered by mosaic floors in the style of the Byzantine era.
            On top of this mountain there is also a large bronze crucifix made by Italian artist, Giovanni Fantoni. This is a symbol of the pillar wrapped by a serpent made by the prophet Moses (Numbers 21:4-9) and also as a symbol of the Cross of Jesus as it is written in John 3:14, 'And just as Moses lifted up the serpent in the wilderness, so the Son of Man must also lift up the serpent in the wilderness. exalted, that everyone who believes in Him may have eternal life.'

        </span>
    </li>
    <li class='text-justify font-weight-bold mb-3'>
        <strong>MADABA</strong> <br>
        <span class='font-weight-normal'>
            Madaba is the name of a province in central Jordan. The provincial capital of the same name is Madaba. Madaba is located in the southwest about 30 kilometers from the capital Amman. The city of Madaba was previously an ancient city named Medeba which is written several times in the Old Testament Bible, including in the book of Numbers 21:30, Joshua 13:9, Joshua 13:16, Isaiah 15:2, I Chronicles 19:7.
            The city with an area of ​​39,440 square kilometers has a population of 84,000 people and the city is also called the City of Mosaics because it is famous for its mosaics, which date back to the Byzantine and Ummayad times in the Holy Land. In the early days of Christianity, Madaba was an important city for transit trade routes.
            In this city stands a church, namely the Church of St. George in which there is a mosaic map of the ancient holy land which is estimated to be from the 6th century, but the map is no longer intact because the city of Madaba was hit by an earthquake in 746. The mosaic map is now placed on the church floor.

        </span>
    </li>
</ol>
